      <scopecontent id="aspace_d07c6259e2d6c80c45a544c6e5bfca65">
         <head>Content Description</head>
         <p>This small collection documents Schiller's use of fleurons, or printer's flowers, to make complicated visual imagery.  His designs are primarily printed as broadsides.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      <bioghist id="aspace_1eeca6283637fe60bd5bf622f83cc185">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Albert Schiller (1898-1970) was born in Russia and immigrated to the United States in 1904. After leaving high school at the age of 17, Schiller worked in a printshop in Harlem before becoming the type director of the J. Walter Thompson Agency in 1918. From 1924 until 1959, he served as the typographic art director of Advertising Agencies' Service Company, Inc. While there, he produced many typographic compositions and pioneered his innovative "type pictures." To create his type pictures, which often served as the company's Christmas cards for clients, Schiller used printer's ornaments and fleurons to form elaborate scenes of architecture, figures, and decorative borders. After retiring from the Advertising Agencies' Service Company, Schiller established an advertising industry consulting firm, Typographic Laboratory. During his lifetime, his work was exhibited in museums and universities, as well as the Los Angeles Public Library, to which he donated a collection of his type pictures. Schiller died on July 22, 1970 in Brooklyn, New York at the age of 71.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <acqinfo id="aspace_2be14d746a76cd32503017c88a1568d1">
         <head>Immediate Source of Acquisition</head>
         <p>Gift of Albert Schiller, 1966.</p>
      </acqinfo>
